INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6d49577b-829f-4428-84d7-d9723ab9d3f3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Next.js App Router — File-Based Routing as Architecture$escape$,
  $escape$The App Router doesn't just map URLs to components — it enforces a colocation model where each route segment owns its full request lifecycle. Drop a `loading.tsx` beside your `page.tsx` and Next.js automatically wraps it in a `<Suspense>` boundary. Add `error.tsx` and you get an `ErrorBoundary` scoped to that segment — parent segments remain interactive when a child throws. `layout.tsx` persists across navigations without remounting, making it the right place for context providers and persistent UI like sidebars.

This means your folder structure *is* your architecture. A `app/dashboard/settings/` directory implicitly defines a nested layout tree, a scoped loading shell, and an isolated error surface. Route groups (`(group)/`) let you share layouts without polluting the URL. Parallel routes (`@slot/`) let two independent segments render in the same layout. When you think in segments instead of pages, feature boundaries map 1:1 to directories — making code-splitting, error isolation, and streaming feel like natural byproducts of how you organize files.$escape$,
  $escape$app/
  dashboard/
    layout.tsx          // persists on sub-navigation
    loading.tsx         // Suspense boundary — streams immediately
    error.tsx           // ErrorBoundary scoped to /dashboard/**
    page.tsx            // default export → /dashboard
    settings/
      page.tsx          // /dashboard/settings
      loading.tsx       // independent Suspense shell
    (overview)/
      analytics/
        page.tsx        // /dashboard/analytics — shares dashboard layout$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
