INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a1834d67-fb0b-4726-bb09-f516dc380a7d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Next.js — Type-Safe Route Params, Search Params, and Loaders with Zod$escape$,
  $escape$Next.js App Router gives you `params` and `searchParams` as plain `unknown` objects — no type safety by default. Zod closes that gap without any extra library overhead.

Define a schema per route segment. In a `[slug]/page.tsx`, parse `params` with `z.object({ slug: z.string() })`. For search params like `?page=2&sort=asc`, parse the `searchParams` prop the same way — coerce numeric strings with `z.coerce.number()`.

For Server Actions and Route Handlers acting as loaders, call `.parse()` at the top of the function. This throws a `ZodError` on bad input, which you catch in a `try/catch` or let Next.js bubble to the nearest `error.tsx`.

Pair this with `generateStaticParams` — type the return value against your Zod schema's inferred type to guarantee build-time and runtime shapes match. No more `params.slug as string` casts scattered across components.

This pattern gives you a single source of truth: the schema drives your TypeScript types, your runtime validation, and your error boundaries — all inside Next.js conventions.$escape$,
  $escape$import { z } from 'zod';

const paramsSchema = z.object({ slug: z.string().min(1) });
const searchSchema = z.object({
  page: z.coerce.number().int().positive().default(1),
  sort: z.enum(['asc', 'desc']).default('desc'),
});

export default function PostPage({
  params,
  searchParams,
}: {
  params: unknown;
  searchParams: unknown;
}) {
  const { slug } = paramsSchema.parse(params);
  const { page, sort } = searchSchema.parse(searchParams);
  // slug, page, sort are fully typed — no casts needed
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
